\section{Conclusions}
In summary, we have investigated the interfacial static friction properties of layered electride $\mathrm{Ca}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$ using the vdW-corrected first-principles approach within DFT. Our calculations reveal that the system exhibits strong interlayer Coulomb attractive forces, but an ultralow friction behavior. The findings are fundamentally different from conventional layered lubricant materials, such as graphite, $h$-BN, and $\mathrm{MoS}_{2}$, where the interlayer bonding is decided by the relative weak $\mathrm{vdW}$ interactions. We used electronic structures to explain the ultralow interfacial friction of $\mathrm{Ca}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$. The uniform interfacial charge distribution brings about a small energy barrier along the sliding path and the easily cleaved nature of $\mathrm{Ca}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$. Because of the large interlayer adsorption, $\mathrm{Ca}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$ will not fall off easily when it is used as lubricant, so it can be considered as a kind of green, anti-wear lubrication material. Our results thus identify a class of promising 2D nanolubricants and enrich the physical understanding of friction mechanisms.

